The International '''Arnold Schönberg Prize''' was established in 2001, and named after the Austrian composer [[Arnold Schönberg]], thanks to the initiative of [[Kent Nagano]], the former principal conductor and musical director of the [[Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin]], together with [[Deutschlandradio]].<ref name=kulturpreise>{{cite web |url=http://www.kulturpreise.de/web/preise_info.php?preisd_id=20064 |title=Arnold-Schönberg-Preis |date=2013 |website=Online-Ausgabe des Handbuchs der Kulturpreise |language=German |access-date=4 June 2017}}</ref> The prize is awarded by the [[Arnold Schönberg Center]] (Vienna, Austria) to international composers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wienerzeitung.at/nachrichten/english_news/208171_Difficult-decisions-force-later-awarding-of-Arnold-Schoenberg-Prize.html |title=Difficult decisions force later awarding of Arnold Schoenberg Prize |date=2001 |website=wienerzeitung.at |publisher=[[Wiener Zeitung]] |access-date=23 June 2017}}</ref> The prize money is €12,500.<ref name=kulturpreise />
==Winners==
* 2001 [[George Benjamin (composer)|George Benjamin]] * 2004 [[Jörg Widmann]] * 2005 [[Unsuk Chin]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Kort |first=Christiane |date=10 March 2005 |title=Arnold Schönberg Preis für Unsuk Chin |url=http://www.deutschlandfunkkultur.de/arnold-schoenberg-preis-fuer-unsuk-chin.1013.de.html?dram:article_id=164788 |work=deutschlandfunkkultur.de |location= |language=German |access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref> * 2006 [[Aribert Reimann]] * 2008 [[Helmut Oehring]]
