{{Infobox motorsport championship | name = Formula 4 UAE Championship | logo = | image-size = | caption = | category = [[Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile|FIA]] [[Formula 4]] | country = United Arab Emirates | region = | inaugural = 2016 | inaugural2 = | folded = | classes = | drivers = | teams = | constructors = [[Tatuus]] | engines = [[Abarth]] | tyres = [[Dunlop Tyres|Dunlop]] | champion driver = {{flagicon|BEL}} Charles Weerts | champion team = {{flagicon|ARE}} Dragon [[Motopark Academy|Motopark]] F4 | manufacturer = | constructor = | website = [http://www.f4uae.com/ Official website] | current_season = 2017–18 Formula 4 UAE Championship }}
Starting in the 2015–16 season, the all new '''[[Formula 4]] UAE Championship''' will be launched by the [[Federation Internationale de l'Automobile]], and its national affiliate the [[Automobile & Touring Club of the United Arab Emirates|Automobile & Touring Club of the United Arab Emirates (ATCUAE)]], who will act as the championship's promoter.<ref>http://www.fia.com/news/formula-4-launched-uae</ref>
==History==
In 2013, the FIA Single seat commission announced their intention to introduce a new category of single seat racing in order to bridge the gap between karting and [[Formula 3]].<ref>http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/106219</ref>
Throughout the following two years, the ATCUAE has worked to develop a Formula 4 championship for the UAE, which will be the first in the Middle East and North African region. One of the first steps taken was to appoint Dubai based AUH Motorsports to manage the championship, based on their experience and expertise in having run the regional [[Radical Sportscars]] series for several years.<ref>http://www.dubaiautodrome.com/tracktalk/2015/12/atcuae-and-auh-motorsport-announce-formula-4-championship/</ref>
In February 2016, the championship was launched in spectacular fashion in front of the world's tallest building, the [[Burj Khalifa]] in Dubai, with the public unveiling of the car undertaken by [[Nahyan bin Mubarak Al Nahyan|HH Nahyan bin Mubarak Al Nahyan]], the Minister of Culture and Knowledge Development and Chairman of the [[General Authority for Youth and Sports Welfare in UAE|General Authority for Youth and Sports Welfare]], and [[Mohammed Ben Sulayem]], President of the ATCUAE.<ref>http://www.thenational.ae/sport/motorsport/uae-formula-4-championship-holds-promise-for-new-generation-of-emirati-drivers</ref>
Following the launch in February 2016, the car was given its first test around the Dubai Autodrome, driven by Dubai-born [[Indy Lights]] driver [[Ed Jones (racing driver)|Ed Jones]].<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3FEW1uvA8s0</ref>
==Format==
The inaugural 2016–17 championship will feature eighteen races over six weekends, four of which will be held at the [[Yas Marina Circuit]] in Abu Dhabi, with the remaining two at the [[Dubai Autodrome]].<ref>http://www.f4uae.com/calendar</ref>
==Car== {{also|Tatuus F4-T014}} The championship features [[Tatuus]] designed and built cars.<ref>http://www.tatuus.it/formula4.php</ref> The cars are constructed out of carbon fibre and feature a monocoque chassis. The engine is a 1.4 turbo [[Abarth]].
This combination of chassis and engine is the same as that already used in the [[Italian F4 Championship]],<ref>http://www.f4championship.com/</ref> [[F4 Spanish Championship]],<ref>http://f4spain.com/car/</ref> [[ADAC Formula 4]]<ref>http://www.adac-motorsport.de/adac-formel-4/uk/autodetails-2016/adac-formel-4-1531</ref> and [[SMP F4 Championship]].<ref>http://smpf4championship.com/</ref>
