{{Infobox news event |title=London Beer Flood |image_name = The manor house of Toten Hall - 1813.gif |caption = Toten Hall house in Tottenham Court Road. |image_alt = A street scene in St. Giles the year before the flood. |date = 17 October 1814 <ref name=greenberg /> |time = |place = [[St Giles in the Fields|St. Giles]], [[London]], [[England]] |coordinates = {{coord|51.51656|-0.13014|type:event_region:GB|format=dms|display=inline,title}} |cause = Structural failure |casualties1 = 8 dead <ref name=greenberg /> |casualties2 = Unknown number injured }}
The '''London Beer Flood''' happened on 17 October 1814<ref>{{cite book|title=The Oxford Companion to Beer|page=48}}</ref> in the parish of [[St Giles in the Fields|St. Giles]], [[London]], [[England]]. At the [[Meux's Brewery|Meux and Company Brewery]]<ref name="greenberg">{{cite book|last=Greenberg|first=Michael I.|title=Disaster!: A Compendium of Terrorist, Natural, and Man-made Catastrophes|publisher=Jones & Bartlett Publishers|pages=156|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EZAdQAuPyKAC&pg=PA156&dq=%22beer+flood%22&hl=nl&sig=Y6Ha_T9sgglenbul8-ZzlGoTUaY|isbn=0-7637-3989-8}}</ref> in [[Tottenham Court Road]],<ref name="greenberg" /><ref name="bookoflists">{{cite book|last=Rennison|first=Nicholas|title=The Book of Lists: London|publisher=Canongate Books Ltd|date=2 November 2006|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Book-Lists-London-Nicholas-Rennison/dp/1841956767|isbn=978-1-84195-676-3}}</ref> a huge [[storage tank|vat]] containing over {{convert|135000|impgal|L}} of [[beer]] ruptured, causing other vats in the same building to succumb in a [[domino effect]]. As a result, more than {{convert|323000|impgal|L}} of beer burst out and gushed into the streets. The wave of beer destroyed two homes and crumbled the wall of the Tavistock Arms pub, killing teenage employee Eleanor Cooper under the rubble.<ref name="expages">[https://web.archive.org/web/20060117063012/http://www.expage.com/page/beerflood London Beer Flood] at Expages.com (archived version)</ref> Within minutes neighbouring George Street and New Street were swamped, seriously injuring a mother, and killing a daughter and young neighbour who were taking tea. The beer also surged through a room of people gathered for a wake, killing five of them.<ref>[http://www.funlondontours.com/news/london-beer-flood-1814 The London Beer Flood of 1814]</ref>
==History== The brewery was among the poor houses and tenements of the St Giles [[rookery (slum)|Rookery]], where whole families lived in basement rooms that quickly filled with beer. At least eight people were known to have [[Drowning|drowned]] in the flood or died from injuries.
The brewery was eventually taken to court over the accident, but the disaster was ruled to be an [[Act of God]] by the judge and jury, leaving no one responsible.<ref name="Rennison2010">{{cite book|last=Rennison|first=Nick|title=Book of Lists London|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HWBquVNVZMUC&pg=PA149|accessdate=13 December 2013|year=2010|publisher=Canongate Books|isbn=978-1-84767-666-5|page=149}}</ref> There were speculations of corruption regarding the court ruling but no official statement was made. The company found it difficult to cope with the financial implications of the disaster, with a significant loss of sales made worse because they had already paid duty on the beer. They made a successful application to Parliament reclaiming the duty which allowed them to continue trading.<ref name="BHO">[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=22171 ''Industries: Brewing''] (British History Online) accessed 10 January 2009</ref>
The brewery was demolished in 1922, and the [[Dominion Theatre]] later occupied part of the site. In 2012, a local pub, the Holborn Whippet, started to mark this event with a vat of [[porter (beer)|porter]] brewed especially for the day.{{citationneeded|date=August 2017}}
