The '''Myponga Pop Festival''' was a music festival which took place on a farm near [[Myponga, South Australia]] from 30 January to 1 February 1971.<ref name="Can Times Feb71">{{cite news | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article110452717 | title = $6,000 Missing as Pop Show Ends in Chaos | newspaper = [[The Canberra Times]] | volume = 45 | issue = 12,724 | date = 2 February 1971 | accessdate = 15 May 2017 | page = 3 | via = [[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref> Its promoters were Alex Innocenti, Trevor Brien and Music Power's Hamish Henry.<ref name="Kimball"/><ref name="Rawlins"/><ref name="MusicPower">{{cite web | author1 = Music Power | title = Music Power presents at Myponga, South Australia a festival of progressive pop music: January 30-31, February 1 | publication-date = 1970 | publisher = Music Power | url = http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/214375428 | accessdate = 16 May 2017 | quote = Summary: Information leaflet promoting the first Australian Festival of Progressive Music, held at Myponga, South Australia, January 30-February 1, 1971. Also known as the Myponga Festival. Includes location map, general information and a list of international, interstate and South Australian performers. }}</ref> The festival was headlined by heavy metal pioneers, [[Black Sabbath]]. [[Cat Stevens]] was advertised as co-headline artist at the festival but he cancelled to perform in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name="Kimball"/><ref name="Rawlins"/> The compere was Adrian Rawlins, who wrote of his experiences at Myponga, and other festivals, in his book ''Festivals in Australia: an Intimate History '' (1982).<ref name="Kimball"/><ref name="Rawlins">{{Citation | author1 = Rawlins, Adrian | title = Festivals in Australia: an Intimate History | publication-date = 1982 | publisher = D.T.E.-Q. for A. Rawlins | isbn = 978-0-9592131-0-2 }}</ref> Another international act was Syrius, (from Hungary, see [[Jackie Orszaczky]]).<ref name="Kimball"/>

Australian artists included [[Daddy Cool (band)|Daddy Cool]], [[Spectrum]], [[Fraternity (band)|Fraternity]], [[Billy Thorpe and the Aztecs]], [[Fanny Adams (band)|Fanny Adams]], [[Jeff St John|Jeff St John's Copperwine]] with [[Wendy Saddington]], [[Company Caine]] and [[Chain (band)|Chain]].<ref name="Kimball">{{cite web | archiveurl = http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/35967/20030624-0000/www.milesago.com/Festivals/myponga.htm | url = http://www.milesago.com/festivals/myponga.htm | title = Performance – Festivals – Myponga Festival, 1971 | last1 = Kimball | first1 = Duncan | first2 = Carl | last2 = Belle |first3 = Vince | last3 = Lovegrove | authorlink3 = Vince Lovegrove | first4 = John | last4 = Low | first5 = Sam | last5 = Pickering | first6 = Terry | last6 = Stacey | publisher = Milesago: Australasian Music and Popular Culture 1964–1975. Ice Productions | archivedate = 24 June 2003 | date = May 2003 | accessdate = 16 May 2017 }}</ref><ref name="Davies">{{cite web | url = http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/entertainment/music/daddy-cool/news-story/bac55f5b950ac998cb2369823db8f60a?nk=44df5d55099a8b5686dcd72bb2c88ad0-1494819670 | title = Myponga part of rock history | last = Davies | first = Nathan | work = [[Sunday Mail (Adelaide)|Sunday Mail]] | date = 20 June 2010 | accessdate = 15 May 2017 }}</ref>

''[[The Canberra Times]]''{{'}} correspondent reported that the "festival rocked to a close tonight after taking l{{frac|1|2}} days to warm up. The pop crowd, estimated at 8,000, started arriving at the 62-acre farm at Myponga early on Saturday morning. Most of them had brought plenty of alcohol and, although violence did not erupt, the atmosphere at the festival was tense at times."<ref name="Can Times Feb71"/> The promoters did not make any profit.<ref name="McFarlane">{{cite book | last1 = McFarlane | first1 = Ian | authorlink1 = Ian McFarlane | title = [[Encyclopedia of Australian Rock and Pop]] | chapter = Encyclopedia entry for 'Festivals' | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20040806231517/http://www.whammo.com.au/encyclopedia.asp?articleid=593 | chapterurl = http://www.whammo.com.au/encyclopedia.asp?articleid=593 | year = 1999 | publisher = [[Allen & Unwin]] | location = [[St Leonards, New South Wales|St Leonards, NSW]] | archivedate = 12 July 2004 | isbn = 1-86508-072-1 }}</ref>

In March 2013 Black Sabbath's [[Ozzy Osbourne]] recalled the group's debut Australian performance, "That was the Myponga Pop Festival if I remember right? Management told us we'd have an exact copy of our amplifiers there, which we thought was great, but when we got there they were nothing like our amplifiers! But you know what? You get up there and do your best and I had a good time. I remember we had a big party at the hotel and some chicks there got absolutely shit-faced and were throwing up everywhere and we had to send them home. I don't remember much on the sex front after that..."<ref name="McLennan">{{cite web | archiveurl = http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/134238/20140724-0001/www.ripitup.com.au/music/article/black-sabbath-ozzy-osbourne-interview.html | url = http://www.ripitup.com.au/music/article/black-sabbath-ozzy-osbourne-interview.html | title = Black Sabbath: Ozzy Osbourne Interview | last = McLennan | first = Scott | work = Rip It Up! | archivedate = 24 July 2014 | date = 14 March 2013 | accessdate = 15 May 2017 }}</ref>

