{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}} {{Politics of Uruguay}}
'''General elections''' were held in [[Uruguay]] on 25 November 1984,<ref name=N1>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] (2005) ''Elections in the Americas: A data handbook, Volume II'', p494 {{ISBN|978-0-19-928358-3}}</ref> the first since the [[1973 Uruguayan coup d'état|1973 coup]]. Since then the country had been run by a [[Civic-military dictatorship of Uruguay|civic-military dictatorship]]. The electoral process was considered transparent and marked the end of the dictatorship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lr21.com.uy/comunidad/342242-calendiario-871 |title=Remembering the 1984 elections |accessdate=2012-05-17}}</ref> The result was a victory for the [[Colorado Party (Uruguay)|Colorado Party]], which won the most seats in the [[Chamber of Deputies of Uruguay|Chamber of Deputies]] and received the most votes in the presidential election.
